explanation:
OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET - This macro/accessor is used to map the token to an implementation table entry. It may expand to a sequence that performs comparisons (or calls functions) which could use memcmp on strings; the macro definition must be inspected for any memcmp usage.

OS_ObjectIndexFromToken - The static call graph shows this function is the likely implementation used by the table-get macro. It converts a token to an object index and could compare token fields (e.g. names) using memcmp; its implementation must be checked for memcmp-on-string usage.

OS_object_token_t - The code dereferences *token. The concrete type and layout determine whether *token yields an integer index (safe) or contains/points to string data that might be compared with memcmp. Knowing the type is necessary to rule out hidden string comparisons.

OS_impl_condvar_table - The table object passed into OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; its definition (type/structure) may influence how the lookup is implemented (e.g. keyed by name) and whether any lookup routine performs string comparisons using memcmp.

OS_impl_condvar_internal_record_t - The record type of the table entries; inspecting its fields shows whether the lookup logic needs to compare string fields inside the record (which could use memcmp). Also needed to confirm that the only field used in this function is the pthread cond var (cv), so no string comparison occurs here.
